<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two Soviet cosmonauts successfully docked their Soyuz TM-8 spacecraft with the 
Mir orbiting space station, the official Tass news agency said. "Everything is 
in order on board, and the cosmonauts feel well," Tass said. The Mir station 
has been vacant for more than four months. Commander Alexander S. Viktorenko 
and engineer Alexander A. Serebrov, who blasted off from the Baikonur 
Cosmodrome in Soviet Central Asia early Wednesday, will remain aboard Mir for 
six months. Along with the cosmonauts, scientists are sending up two modules to 
expand the station's living space and upgrade its scientific capabilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
