THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government invited Sinhalese and Tamil rebels for peace talks 
with all political parties in a bid to end ethnic conflicts in which 16,000 
people have been killed. Officials said that in the latest violence, 32 people 
were killed in two days by Sinhalese ultranationalist guerrillas waging a 
campaign of assassinations and strikes to try to topple the government of 
President Ranasinghe Premadasa. The guerrilla groups and 23 recognized 
political parties were included in the invitation to a peace conference Sept. 
13. 
</P>
