<P>
NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
MARILYN MONROE LETTER NETS $7,150 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A handwritten letter by Marilyn Monroe was sold for $7,150, setting a record 
for an auction price for a letter by a movie star, according to a specialist in 
autograph auctions. 
</P>
<P>
The auction Thursday night broke the old record of $6,600 paid in September, 
1987, for a handwritten letter by actress Greta Garbo, said Herman Darvick, who 
stages autograph auctions six times a year. 
</P>
<P>
The record does not include one movie actor -- the one who became President. A 
handwritten letter by Ronald Reagan praising Frank Sinatra once sold for 
$12,500, but his White House connection made a large difference, Darvick said. 
</P>
<P>
The Monroe letter, in an envelope postmarked Jan. 17, 1945, is actually signed 
Norma Jeane, Monroe's given name. She was 18 when she wrote it. 
</P>
