<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
ENGLISH MATCH WITH DUTCH CANCELED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The English Football Assn. voted today to cancel a trip by the national soccer 
team to the Netherlands in December because of a fear of hooliganism. 
</P>
<P>
The decision came a day after the British government asked the association to 
call off the match and two days after English hooliganism re-emerged during a 
World Cup match in Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
The association said members of its executive committee, who were canvassed by 
telephone, voted unanimously to call off the exhibition match set for Dec. 13 
in Rotterdam. 
</P>
<P>
Sports Minister Colin Moynihan sent a letter to the association Thursday 
seeking cancellation of the match "in the interests of the future of English 
football and of the country as a whole." 
</P>
<P>
More than 100 English fans were arrested Wednesday night for vandalism and 
rampaging through central Stockholm before the World Cup qualifying match 
against Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
